The Microtubule-Dependent Formation of a Tubulovesicular Network with Characteristics of the ER from Cultured Cell Extracts

Sandra L. Dabora*t and Michael R Sheetz* * Department of Cell Biology and Physiology Washington University Medical School 660 South Euclid Avenue St. Louis, Missouri 63110 University of Connecticut Health Center Department of Physiology Farmington, Connecticut 06032
Summary
The formation of a dynamic tubulovesicular membrane network that resembles the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) has been observed in extracts of cultured chick embryo fibroblasts (CEF cells) using videoenhanced differential interference contrast microscopy. Initially, membranes in the CEF extracts appeared amorphous and aggregated, but with time, membrane tubules moved out along stationary microtubules. The membrane tubules formed new branches on intersecting microtubules and fused with other branches to form a network of interconnected polygons. The tubulovesicular network was solubilized by detergent and took on a beaded morphology in a hypotonic buffer. Formation of the tubulovesicular network required ATP and microtubules. The network did not contain elements of the plasma membrane, Golgi apparatus, or mitochondria but could be labeled with ER markers. We suggest that the tubulovesicular network contains components from the ER and is formed by membrane associated motors moving upon microtubules in a process we call microtubuledependent tethering.
Introduction
The endoplasmic reticulum (ER) is an intracellular organelle whose morphology is dependent on microtubules. The ER was named by Porter (1953) for its extensive reticular morphology in whole mounts of cultured cells observed using the electron microscope. The ER has since been shown to play an important role in protein and lipid synthesis, membrane traffic, and calcium sequestration. Electron microscopy studies have shown that the ER has a large surface area because of its reticular morphology and also that ER is often associated with microtubules (Buckley and Porter, 1975; Franke, 1971).This association was investigated by Terasaki et al. (1986) using fluorescent labeling techniques to study the ER and microtubules in fixed cells. When the ER was visualized with the cyanine dye, 3,3'-dihexyloxacarbocyanine iodide (DiOC6(3)), it was arranged in a polygonal network and appeared to be associated with microtubules, particularly in the lamellipodia where individual microtubules and ER tubules could be observed. When the microtubules in the cell were depolymerized, the ER network gradually retracted toward the cell cen-

ter. If the microtubules repolymerized, the ER network extended to its original morphology. This work suggested that microtubules play a role in maintaining the morphology of the ER.
Studies of Lee and Chen (1988) have demonstrated that the ER (labeled with DiOC6(3)) is a very dynamic or.. ganetle in living cells. Membrane tubules extend from the existing network, fuse to form new polygons, and existing polygons contract often until they disappear. The striking morphology and the dynamics of the ER suggest that an active, energy requiring process may be involved in its formation. Since the ER is associated with microtubules, these cytoskeletal elements may support ER formation and movement. Microtubule dependent movements of vesicular organelles are a means for intracellular transport in many kinds of eukaryotic cells (Schnapp et al., 1985; Allan and Kreis, 1986; Koonce and Schliwa, 1985; Kachar et al., 1987; Matteoni and Kreis, 1987), and microtubule-based motility may be responsible for the formation and movement of the ER network as well.
In vitro assays have been used in attempts to understand microtubule-based organelle translocation, and these assays have shown that the movement of membrane bound organelles along purified microtubules requires the presence of soluble cytosolic factors and ATP. This type of soluble motor activity has been observed in squid neuronal tissue, sea urchin egg cytoplasm, and most recently in cultured vertebrate cell extracts (Schnapp et al., 1985; Pryer et al., 1986; Dabora and Sheetz, 1988). These assays have led to the identification of the microtubule-dependent motor enzyme, kinesin, which moves toward the plus end of the microtubule (anterograde direction in axons; Vale et al., 1985b). A second microtubuledependent motor activity that is directed toward the minus end of microtubules (retrograde in axons) has also been identified (Vale et al., 1985c). This minus end directed motor has many characteristics of dynein and could be classified as a cytoplasmic dynein (Pratt et al., 1984; Lye et al., 1987; Paschal et al., 1987; Paschal and Vallee, 1987). Although these two soluble microtubule-based motors may be involved in organelle motility, additional factors are also required. Recent studies of the motility of highly purified organetles have demonstrated that kinesin alone is not sufficient to produce organelle motility. A soluble factor that appears to associate with kinesin is also necessary for organelle movement (Schroer, Schnapp, Reese, and Sheetz, unpublished data). Organelle motility is, therefore, a complex process that appears to require active organelles, microtubules, motors, and accessory proteins.
An in vitro system that reconstitutes ER network formation and dynamics would provide a useful experimental system in which to study the molecules involved in ER formation and function. We describe here a cell-free system in which a dynamic tubulovesicular network forms in vitro in the presence of microtubules and ATP.The network has the highly branched morphology characteristic of the ER and can be labeled with ER markers. The formation in

