Results
Tubulovesicular Network Formation In Vitro Is Microtubule- and ATP-Dependent To study the interactions of tubulovesicular organelles with microtubules, we have developed an in vitro assay for the formation of a tubulovesicular network from extracts of cultured chick embryo fibroblasts (CEF cells). CEF cell extract supernatant (supernantant B) and membrane pellet (pellet B) fractions were generated by differential centrifugation (see Experimental Procedures; also Dabora and Sheetz, 1988). Supernatant B contained tubulin, organelle motors, and small spherical organelles. Pellet B contained larger organelles that were the precursors of the tubulovesicular network (Figure 1A). Supernatant B and resuspended pellet B were mixed in a ratio of 4:1 in the presence of 20 ~M taxol and 1 mM GTP to induce tubulin polymerization. ATP (2 mM) was added, and the sample was observed with video-enhanced differential interference contrast (DIC) microscopy as described by Schnapp (1986). Over the course of 30 min to 2 hr (at room temperature), linear membrane tubules formed from amorphous membrane aggregates by movement out on the lower contrast microtubules (Figure 1B). There was no evidence of the linear tubules in the original aggregates. The extension of the membrane tubules sometimes occured concomitantly with a distortion of the aggregates in a manner that suggested that a pulling force was being applied at the site where the membrane tubule left the aggregate. Primarily, the network was two-dimensional, although it did not adhere to the glass surface over most of its length, as evidenced by Brownian motion of the tubule. Mem-

brane tubules were supported on or above the glass by attachments to microtubules. The microtubules were aligned parallel to the coverslip by adsorption to the glass, and they usually remained stationary (Dabora and Sheetz, 1988). Polygons of membrane tubules were formed initially by the fusion of membrane tubules from the same aggregate, but at later times, membrane tubules often formed a continuous network extending over millimeters of the coverslip surface.
The formation of the membrane network was microtubule- and ATP-dependent. If taxol and GTP were omitted and colchicine (20 ~M) was added, microtubules were not present and the membrane network did not form. The microtubule dependence of network formation was also demonstrated in experiments where membrane, soluble factors, and microtubules were separated into different fractions (see Experimental Procedures). If membranes and supernatant were recombined without microtubules, no network was formed. Likewise, if the endogenous ATP was depleted with hexokinase and glucose (see Experimental Procedures) and no ATP was added, the network did not form.
In order to determine whether the membrane networks could form in extracts prepared from other cell types, a mammalian cell line was tested. Similar networks formed in extracts of African Green Monkey kidney cells (the same cell type used in the living cell studies of Lee and Chen [1988]).
Characterization of Membrane Networks: Shapes, Dynamics, and Composition The membrane network that formed in vitro had a striking morphology consisting of interconnected polygons (see Figure 1B). This morphology was similar to that of the ER in fixed and living cells (Terasaki et al., 1984; Sardet, 1984; Quader et al., 1987; Lee and Chen, 1988). Prominent char-

