Frequent movements and shape changes were observed in these in vitro tubular networks. As shown in Figure 2A, network branches clearly moved along stationary microtubules. The velocity of this movement was 0.5 _ 0.5 #m/sec (mean +__SD). It was sometimes difficult to distinguish between the possibilities of movement of membrane tubules along stationary microtubules and movement of a membrane tubule bound to a microtubule that was gliding along the glass surface thereby pulling out the membrane tubule. However, moving membrane tubules could switch to move along an intersecting microtubule (Figure 2B), demonstrating that the membrane tubules were moving along the underlying microtubules. In addition, membrane tubules were occasionally observed to extend, recoil, and extend again on the same microtubule (this also illustrated elastic properties of the network). Although soluble microtubule motors can support movement of microtubules on glass (Vale et al., 1985a; Porter

et al., 1987; Dabora and Sheetz, 1988), in these extracts, most microtubules were attached firmly to the glass, supporting our suggestion that movement of membrane tubule branches on stationary microtubules was the predominant activity.
Since the membranes in pellet B were initially amorphous aggregates, it seemed likely that fusion between membrane tubules was required to form the interconnected polygonal network. Consistent with this assumption, we observed that membrane tubules did fuse with one another. Figure 2B shows a membrane tubule moving along a microtubule until it meets another branch of the membrane network. The two membranes fuse, transiently giving rise to a new polygon that contracts into a new shape. This is similar to the phenomenon of ER ring closure observed by Lee and Chen (1988) in epithelial cells.
