The osmotic properties of this network were also investigated. If the network was subjected to hypotonic conditions (50% PMEE), the membrane tubules swelled at intersection points and became beaded in appearance (Figure 4). This change in morphology was reversible because the networks returned to their original appearance when the original buffer (PMEE) was returned, This behavior would be expected for a semipermeable biological membrane enclosing a lumenal aqueous phase. The beaded structure seen in Figure 4B may result from osmotically driven swelling of the tubules.
The actual diameter of the network cannot be derived from the light microscope images; therefore, portions of the network were viewed in the electron microscope after rotary shadowing of freeze-fractured and etched samples (the technique of Heuser and Evans, 1980). The tubules had a larger diameter than microtubules averaging 80100 nm with a range from 20-200 nm (see Figure 5). There were also regions where the membrane was not tubular but rather formed more planar structures (see Figure 5). Identification of the molecular composition of the structures on the network awaits additional studies with appropriate antibody probes.
