Tubulovesicular Network Contains Components of the ER Several different approaches were taken to determine the biochemical characteristics and cellular sources of the membrane that formed networks. Because the dye, DiOC6(3), has previously been shown to preferentially label the ER (Terasaki et al., 1984; Quader and Schnepf, 1986; Dailey and Bridgman, unpublished data), we used it to stain these in vitro networks. The tubulovesicular network (Figure 6C) had a labeling pattern similar to the ER in intact cells (Figure 6A; Terasaki et al., 1984, 1986), suggesting that the tubulovesicular network contained components of the ER. Fluorescent labeling studies were used to determine whether mitochondria, plasma membrane, and Golgi apparatus components contributed to this membrane network. In vitro networks were labeled with rhodamine 123 (see Experimental Procedures), a vital dye for mitochondria (Johnson et al., 1980). Although labeled mitochondria were observed in the sample, they remained as round or oblong vesicles and did not contribute to the network. Evidence that the plasma membrane was not a component of this membrane network came from experiments in which the plasma membranes of intact cells were labeled with rhodamine-concanavalin A prior to homogenization and preparation of the CEF extract (Figure 6B). The networks that were formed from the extracts of the rhodamine-concanavalin-A-labeled cells were not fluorescently labeled (Figure 6D). The majority of the label was found in large membrane fragments of pellet A with some labeling of small, round organelles in pellet B and supernatant B. When cells were labeled prior to homogenization with the fluorescent ceramide analog, C6-NBD-ceramide, the Golgi apparatus was specifically labeled (Lipsky and Pagano, 1985; van Meer et al., 1987). The network prepared from Ce-NBD-ceramide-labeted cells, however, was not fluorescently labeled. Fluores-

