Discussion
The Tubulovesicular Network Formed In Vitro Is Similar to the ER in Intact Cells The dynamic behavior of the tubulovesicular network in vitro is remarkably similar to the behavior of the ER (labeled with DiOC6(3)) in living epithelial cells (Lee and Chen, 1988). In both cases, many three-way junctions are observed, new membrane tubules are constantly extending, and the polygonal structures change shape as membrane tubules move. We have observed many examples of tubule branching, fusion, ring closure, and sliding (categories of movements of ER in living epithelial cells described by Lee and Chen [1988]). The mean velocity of movement of the membrane tubules in vitro (0.5 ~m/sec) is approximately the same as the velocity of movement of spherical organelles in living fibroblasts (Dabora and Sheetz, 1988). A slightly faster velocity (1.1 t~m/sec) for tubule branch movement was observed by Lee and Chen (1988), but this was expected because those studies were done at a higher temperature (37°C). Although microtu-

bules and ER were not simultaneously observed in living cells, the fluorescent labeling studies of Terasaki et al. (1986) in fixed cells indicated that microtubules were involved in ER formation. There are many similarities between the ER network of intact cells and the tubulovesicular network formed in vitro, which suggests that this is a useful cell-free system for the further study of the formation and dynamics of the ER.
Characteristics of the Membrane Network The in vitro tubulovesicular network is a lipid-containing membrane as determined by its detergent solubility (Figure 3) and DiOC6(3) labeling (Figures 6A and 6C). The fluid character of the membrane was most apparent when new branches extended or fused with existing tubules forming three-way junctions, which frequently migrated. These junctions appeared most stable when the angles between tubule branches were 120°. Since membrane tubules and network branch points were often found in places without underlying microtubules, the positions of the branch points appear to move in order to adopt the minimum energy configuration within the constraints imposed by the positions of the microtubule contact points and the nature of the membranes. Similar three-way intersections have been described (Stevens, 1974) as the minimum energy shape of a soap film connecting three points between two glass plates. Qualitatively, the behavior of the network is consistent with that of a cylindrical lipid bilayer in an aqueous environment responding to the application of force at points along its surface.
