Membrane Network Formation: A Possible Mechanism Since the membrane tubules of the network move along

microtubules, microtubule based motors may be involved in the formation of the network. The properties of network tubule movement are similar to the vesicular organelte movement described in earlier studies (Vale et al., 1985a; Gilbert et al., 1985; Dabora and Sheetz, 1988). Membrane tubules and vesicular organelles have similar velocities of movement, and both can switch from one microtubule to another. An attractive hypothesis is that the extension of the endoplasmic reticulum from cell center to periphery requires movement toward the plus ends of microtubutes, which is the direction of kinesin-induced movement.
On the basis of these results, we suggest a possible mechanism, called microtubule-dependent tethering, for network formation (Figure 7). A motor enzyme, such as kinesin or cytoplasmic dynein, binds to sites on the membrane aggregates. The motor then attaches to and moves along a microtubule, pulling out a membrane tubule from the aggregated membrane. This process of tubule formation is analogous to the formation of membrane tethers from erythrocytes or lipid vesicles (Waugh, 1982; Hochmuth et al., 1982). When a force is applied to a point on the erythrocyte membrane, a linear strand or tether forms with a diameter of 10-20 nm. In the present model, a microtubule motor provides the necessary force to draw out a tubule of ER instead of the force applied with a micropipette and micromanipulator on the erythrocyte membrane. An alternative mechanism for producing the network is for membrane attached microtubules to draw out membrane strands by microtubule movement along the glass. While this may happen occasionally in vitro (Sheetz, 1987; Vale, unpublished data), it is unlikely to occur within fibroblasts (Sammak and Borisy, unpublished data). In these studies, we consistently observe the movement of the membrane branches along stationary microtubules (Figure 2); therefore, we suggest that the membrane tubules are tethers pulled by membrane attached motors moving along microtubules.
Conclusion Within eukaryotic cells, the ER constitutes a significant fraction of the intracellular membrane (Alberts et al., 1983). The mechanism by which the membrane reticulum is formed in vivo is not understood, but the participation of microtubules in the formation and maintenance of the ER has been suggested (Terasaki et al., 1986). We show here that a tubulovesicular network analogous to the ER can form in vitro from membranous aggregates in the presence of microtubules and ATP. We propose a mechanism for the formation of this striking in vitro network in which membrane tubules are formed from membrane aggregates by the translocation of point contacts along microtubules, as illustrated in Figure 7.
In living cells, the ER has striking morphological and dynamic characteristics, and it is interesting to speculate that these characteristics may be required for or enhance ER functions such as protein synthesis, lipid synthesis, membrane traffic, and calcium sequestration. The dynamic behavior may be necessary to reorganize and maintain the morphology of the ER throughout the cell cy-

