Experimental Procedures
Materials Chick embryo fibroblasts were prepared from 11 day embryos as described by Kelley and Schlessinger (1978) and maintained in Earle's Minimum Essential Medium supplemented with 3% fetal calf serum. Primary and secondary cultures were used within 5 days after plating for all experiments. Taxol was a gift of Dr. Matthew Suffness. African Green Monkey kidney cells (TC-7 line) were a gift of Dr. Gregg Gunderson. The monoclonal antibody to BiP was a gift of Dr. David Bole. 3,3'dihexyloxacarbocyanine iodide (DiOC6(3)) and rhodamine 123 were obtained from Polysciences, Inc. (Warrington, PA). C6-NBD-ceramide was obtained from Molecular Probes (Eugene, OR). All other reagents were obtained from Sigma (St. Louis, MO).
Formation of Tubulovesicular Network In Vitro from CEF Cell Extracts Supernatant B and pellet B fractions were prepared from CEF cells as previously described (Dabora and Sheetz, 1988). Briefly, cells were harvested, rinsed in PMEE (35 mM PIPES, 5 mM MgSO4, 5 mM EGTA, 0.5 mM EDTA [pH 7.4], containing 1 mM dithiothreitol, 1 mM phenylmethylsulfonyl fluoride, 1 ~g/ml of pepstatin A, 10 p.g/ml of p-tosyI-L-arginine methyl ester, 10 pg/ml of N-e-benzoyI-L-arginine methyl ester, 10 p.g/ml of L-l-tosylamide phenylethyl-chloromethyl ketone, 1 p.g/mlof leupeptin, 10 p.g/ml of soybean trypsin inhibitor), and homogenized. Nuclei and cell debris were removed by centrifuging at 1000 x g (for 10 min at 0°C), and the resulting supernatant (supernatant A) was used to prepare supernatant B and pellet B. Supernatant B and pellet B were obtained from supernatant A by centrifugation at 12,000 x g (for 15 min at 0°C). A standard network sample was prepared by mixing 3 pJ of supernatant B, 1 p.Iof pellet B, which had been resuspended in PMEE buffer to the original cell pellet volume (see Dabora and Sheetz, 1988), and 1#1 of a 5x stock of taxol and GTP, to give final concentrations of 20 I~M taxol and 1 mM GTIR The sample was then incubated at 37°C for 15 min to polymerize the endogenous tubulin. ATP (2 mM) was added and the sample was incubated at room temperature (21°C) in a humidified chamber for 30 min to 2 hr. The networks were observed in the sample using video-enhanced DIC optics as described by Schnapp (1986). Velocities of membrane tubule movements along microtubules were measured using a video tracking device described previously (Sheetz et al., 1986), which converts distance moved on the video monitor during a number of elapsed video frames directly to velocity.
In studies using inhibitors, the inhibitor was added with the ATP,and the sample was observed 2 hr later. For ATP depletion, 0.2 mg/ml of hexokinase (180 U/mg) and 6 mM of D-glucose (Davey et al., 1985) were added, and the sample was observed 2 hr later. For the detergent and osmotic sensitivity experiments, a flow chamber was constructed using glass coverslips and silicone vacuum grease. A network sample was prepared in a flow chamber and either detergent (0.05% Triton X-100 in PMEE) or a hypotonic buffer (50% PMEE) was flowed through the chamber until the original buffer was completely replaced.
To demonstrate the microtubule dependence of network formation, supernatant B was further fractionated into soluble factors, membranes, and microtubules. This was done by centrifuging supernatant B (at 100,000 x g for 30 min at 0°C) to pellet membrane bound organelles. Taxol (20 ~M) and GTP (1 mM) were then added to the clarified supernatant B (now containing only soluble factors and tubulin) followed by a 15 min incubation at 37°C to polymerize the tubulin. Microtubules were removed by centrifugation (at 100,000 x g for 30 min at 20°C), leaving soluble factors in the supernatant and microtubules in the pellet. Network samples were set up using this soluble factor fraction (3 #1),pellet B (1 FJ), microtubutes (1 ~t of 1-2 mg/ml, phosphocellulos column purified tubulin prepared from bovine brain [Wii-

liams and Lee, 1982]), plus 2 mM ATP. The microtubule fraction was omitted to show that network formation was microtubule-dependent.
Fluorescence Labeling Experiment For DiOC6(3) labeling, network samples were prepared as described above in a flow chamber. After 2 hr of incubation, the samples were fixed with 3% formaldehyde in PMEE for 3-5 rain, then DiOC6(3) was added (2.5 p.g/ml for 10 sec). The network samples were washed three times with PMEE (the final wash contained 1 mg/ml of p-phenylenediamine to inhibit photobleaching). Intact CEF cells were labeled with DiOC6(3) according to the method of Terasaki et al. (1986). Rhodamine 123 labeling was modified from Johnson et al. (1980). Networks were formed in vitro as described above and incubated in 10 pg/ml of rhodamine 123 in PMEE for 30 min. The sample was then rinsed several times with PMEE.
For double labeling with NBD-C6-ceramide and rhodamine-concanavalin A, cells were first incubated for 30 rain at 4°C with 10 ~M NBD-C6-ceramide and 0.88 mg/ml of bovine serum albumin (fatty acid free) in serum free MEM Earle's, rinsed, and incubated for an additional 2 hr at 21°C (modified from Lipsky and Pagano, 1985; van Meer et al., 1987). Cells were then scraped off the culture dishes, labeled with 40 :~g/ml of rhodamine-concanavalin A for 30 min at 0°C, and washed twice with PMEE. Supernatant B and pellet B fractions were prepared from the labeled cells and used to prepare network samples as described above. CEF cells plated on glass coverslips were also labeled following these protocols to show that NBD-C6-ceramide labeled the Golgi apparatus and rhodamine-concanavalin A labeled the plasma membrane in intact cells.
A monoclonal antibody to BiP was used to detect BiP in cells and in the membrane networks formed in vitro using indirect immunofluorescence. Cells or networks were fixed by freeze substitution according to the method of Bridgman and Reese (1984). The fixed preparations were incubated with the monoclonal antibody to BiP (Bole et al., 1986) and bound antibody was detected using a fluorescein-conjugated rabbit anti-rat second antibody. A control sample was incubated with second antibody alone (no label was detected).
All fluorescence photographs were taken with a photomicrographic camera attached to a Zeiss standard microscope equipped with epifluorescence using the appropriate filter (rhodamine or fluorescein). Kodak Tri-X film was used for all photographs.
Deep Etch Electron Microscopy Deep etch electron microscopy was performed as described by Heuser and Evans (1980) on membrane networks formed in vitro on coverslips and fixed in 2% glutaraldehyde in PMEE.
